      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

Sure=20
I guess:

Boaz Weinstein and his group of bidders revised their offer to buy Sculptor=
 Capital Management Inc., seeking to address some of the concerns the board=
=E2=80=99s special committee outlined in a proxy filing last week, accordin=
g to people familiar with the matter.
While Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid remains at $12.76 a share, it has beefed up i=
ts equity commitments, eliminated risks associated with debt financing and =
increased the damages it would pay if it fails to consummate the transactio=
n, the people said.
Sculptor accepted Rithm Capital Corp.=E2=80=99s lower bid of $11.15 a share=
, or about $639 million, in July. It still preferred that offer as of a fil=
ing on Aug. 30, citing a variety of concerns about the higher bid from the =
other group.
It=E2=80=99s unclear whether Sculptor will be swayed by the amended proposa=
l.=C2=A0

We=20
discussed the board=E2=80=99s concerns last week, and I think they fall int=
o two main buckets:
=09The board seems to think that Weinstein and friends are a bunch of flake=
s who might walk away from the deal, so they want strong deal protections t=
o prevent that.=09The board seems to think that Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fu=
nd=C2=A0clients=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t want Weinstein and friends to take over =
Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds, and Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal (like Rithm=E2=80=99=
s) is contingent on client approval. If the clients say no to Weinstein, th=
en his deal won=E2=80=99t go through and Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders wo=
n=E2=80=99t get the $12.76.

The first concern strikes me as a=C2=A0little=C2=A0silly. The second concer=
n strikes me as more real, but it does seem like the solution would be to=
=C2=A0ask=C2=A0the clients? Like at some level this is a knowable thing; th=
e clients either like the Weinstein group or they don=E2=80=99t, and somebo=
dy should find out.
Anyway it seems like the revised proposal addresses the first concern, =E2=
=80=9Cbeefing up=E2=80=9D the equity commitments and increasing the reverse=
 breakup fee to reduce the risk that Weinstein and friends will just flake =
on the deal. It does not seem to address the second concern.
Elsewhere, Sculptor sent its employees a letter saying it=E2=80=99s having =
a good year:

While we typically do not indulge in pats on the back, especially at this s=
tage of the year, the combination of the achievement thus far and a shiftin=
g macroeconomic landscape calls for an exception.
Our multi-strategy fund is having a terrific year, delivering a net return =
in August of +2.8%, bringing the YTD net return to +12.6%. =E2=80=A6 In opp=
ortunistic credit, net fund performance ranges from +8% to +15% year to dat=
e, as we capitalize on one of the more exciting investment environments we =
have seen in our careers. =E2=80=A6
These results are impressive =E2=80=93 absolute, relative, risk-adjusted, a=
nd in every other way. And importantly, they build on decades of consistent=
 compounding for clients. Of course, we don=E2=80=99t measure ourselves bas=
ed on YTD performance through August and our clients evaluate us over a muc=
h longer period. But when we look to the future, we are excited that across=
 nearly every geography, asset class and investment style, we have a robust=
 pipeline of differentiated and scalable investment ideas.
No matter how loud the volume gets (from talk of a strategic transaction or=
 otherwise), the important stuff is always the same. Work hard, put our cli=
ents first, collaborate with each other and conduct ourselves with integrit=
y and transparency.

I suppose that performance is relevant to the question of whether clients w=
ould prefer the Rithm deal (which would mostly keep current management) or =
the Weinstein deal (less so). The better Sculptor=E2=80=99s performance is,=
 the less vulnerable it probably is to a hostile takeover.

