<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitcoin accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US generally accepted accounting for Bitco=
in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32636693.287427=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDgvZW=
xvbi1tdXNrLXdvcmtzLWhpcy1tYWdpYy1vbi1kb2dlY29pbi1hbmQtYml0Y29pbj9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwOTA3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa5281270" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">
is that</a> it can go down, but not up: If you are a corporation and you bu=
y some Bitcoins, then the Bitcoins are reflected on your balance sheet at t=
heir cost, but you test them every quarter for impairment. If the price has=
 gone down, the Bitcoins are impaired: You reflect their lower value on you=
r balance sheet, and you take a loss on your income statement. If the price=
=C2=A0has gone up, you <em>don=E2=80=99t </em>reflect the higher value on y=
our balance sheet or take a gain in income. (If you=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em=
>the Bitcoins at a higher price, you do have a gain in income.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Accounting is, by default, conservative, and i=
f you come to an accountant and say =E2=80=9Cwe have invented a new sort of=
 digital asset, how should we account for it,=E2=80=9D this is what they wi=
ll come up with.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If you have invented a new sort of magic bean, an accountant=E2=80=99s=
 first guess will be:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The beans are probably worth what you=
 paid for them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you say that th=
e beans=E2=80=99 value went up since you bought them, you=E2=80=99re probab=
ly lying.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you say that the bean=
s=E2=80=99 value went down since you bought them, you=E2=80=99re probably r=
ight.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you get this sort of accounting for Bit=
coin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a very appropriate reaction to a new t=
hing, so you see why Bitcoin got this accounting. But by now there is a big=
 liquid market for Bitcoin and if you say that the value of your Bitcoins w=
ent up, and you point to their trading prices on a bunch of big crypto exch=
anges, at this point your accountants will believe you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32636693.287427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mYXNiL=
WFkb3B0cy1jcnlwdG8tYWNjb3VudGluZy1hbmQtZGlzY2xvc3VyZS1ydWxlLWZvci1jb21wYW5p=
ZXMtNzQ5YWRjNDQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe6bed182" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the accounting =
is changing</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Financial Accounting Standards Board voted=
 to set a new rule on cryptocurrency accounting and disclosure, changes com=
panies holding these assets have argued more accurately reflect their finan=
cial condition. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The FASB, which sets accounting standards for =
U.S. public and private companies and nonprofits, on Wednesday voted unanim=
ously to adopt a new standard that would require businesses to=C2=A0use fai=
r-value accounting for bitcoin and certain other crypto assets. Companies a=
nd accountants have repeatedly rallied for this change, as it would allow t=
hem to recognize losses and gains immediately, and treat digital assets as =
they would some financial assets instead of as indefinite-lived intangible =
assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Public companies=E2=80=99 financial statements=
 will have to disclose their crypto assets, separating them from intangible=
 assets like patents and trademarks, on a quarterly and annual basis. Priva=
te companies must do the same in whichever financial reports they compile. =
Businesses will have to include gains and losses on their crypto assets in =
their net income.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule is set to go into effect for 2025 ann=
ual reports for calendar-year public and private companies, which can adopt=
 the changes early.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not think that the weird accounting is, l=
ike, the=C2=A0<em>main=C2=A0</em>impediment to all of corporate America shi=
fting its working capital from dollars into Bitcoins. But the accounting is=
 annoying, and companies that own have a lot of Bitcoin will <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32636693.287427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMjEvbWljcm9zdHJhdGVneS1wbHV=
tbWV0cy1hcy1zZWMtcmVqZWN0cy1pdHMtYml0Y29pbi1hY2NvdW50aW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MD=
cyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0b=
V90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
ac93d597" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">
grumble about it</a> a bit in their securities filings. (=E2=80=9CAny decre=
ase in their fair values below our carrying values for such assets at any t=
ime subsequent to their acquisition will require us to recognize impairment=
 charges,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32636693.287427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2=
RhdGEvMTMxODYwNS8wMDAwOTUwMTcwMjMwMDE0MDkvdHNsYS0yMDIyMTIzMS5odG0/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB6d2355d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says Tesla Inc.</a>, =E2=80=9Cwhereas we=
 may make no upward revisions for any market price increases until a sale. =
For any digital assets held now or in the future, these charges may negativ=
ely impact our profitability in the periods in which such impairments occur=
 even if the overall market values of these assets increase.=E2=80=9D)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, though, if you are a public company and y=
ou buy Bitcoin and the price of Bitcoin goes up, you have income. That migh=
t make it a bit more attractive to buy Bitcoin.</p>
