<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The board seems to think that Weinste=
in and friends are a bunch of flakes who might walk away from the deal, so =
they want strong deal protections to prevent that.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">The board seems to think that Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fun=
d=C2=A0<em>clients=C2=A0</em>won=E2=80=99t want Weinstein and friends to ta=
ke over Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds, and Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal (like Rithm=
=E2=80=99s) is contingent on client approval. If the clients say no to Wein=
stein, then his deal won=E2=80=99t go through and Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareh=
olders won=E2=80=99t get the $12.76.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first concern strikes me as a=C2=A0<em>lit=
tle=C2=A0</em>silly. The second concern strikes me as more real, but it doe=
s seem like the solution would be to=C2=A0<em>ask=C2=A0</em>the clients? Li=
ke at some level this is a knowable thing; the clients either like the Wein=
stein group or they don=E2=80=99t, and somebody should find out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway it seems like the revised proposal addr=
esses the first concern, =E2=80=9Cbeefing up=E2=80=9D the equity commitment=
s and increasing the reverse breakup fee to reduce the risk that Weinstein =
and friends will just flake on the deal. It does not seem to address the se=
cond concern.</p>
